Text: @FeminismInIndia Regardless of race or age or disability everyone should be tested for sexually transmitted infections. This is especially important for women, since women suffer more frequent and more serious complications from STIs than men.

Text: @FeminismInIndia If left untreated, STIs can cause serious health problems including cervical cancer, liver disease, pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), infertility, and pregnancy problems

@tarshingo My pleasure entirely to be hete on #TARSHIChats 
Thank you!
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChat Disabilities don't make us lesser human beings...We too have right to wear sexy clothes, wear make up express our sexuality as we want
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Till we are considered 'divine' 'superheros' or helpless we would be treated as a separate class and that too a marginalized one
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Removal or barrier, provision of accessibility can make us i..e the persons with disabilities, visible...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats And first step has to come from us only...We need to learn to love our virtues and our scars, our strengths and even our vulnerabilities
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Let us start by trying to change the conventional notion of beauty and sexuality...Let is shun all the stereotypes...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats And at last there has to be a commitment to find beauty in the most unexpected places :)
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats The ultimate goal is to engage in dialogue that centers on the creative potential of every individual in order to bring about social transformation within this visual culture at large
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats We need to fight a war against social oppression and prejudice. Every individual has to make an effort to open his exclusive version of outer beauty embracing his own unique style even in the presence of flaws
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Would the Venus de Milo still be considered one of the great examples of both aesthetic and human beauty if she had both her arms?
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo Here I would like to be a little bit philosophical :) We all know about the ancient Greek sculpture, the Venus de Milo which is immediately recognizable by its missing arms and popularly believed to represent Aphrodite, the Greek goddess of love and beauty. ..
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Let us educate others that aesthetic is sometimes described as one of beauty that is ‚Äúimperfect, impermanent, and incomplete‚Äù.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats To change things our responsibility is to develop a consciousness of beauty even in imperfection and endeavor to reverse the hegemony of ‚ÄòBeing Beautiful' #TARSHIChats
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo All this can in turn impact our own understandings of what it means to be human and what signifies a perfect or happy life...#TARSHIChats
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats The desire for human perfection can lead to medical conditions such as obsessive compulsive disorder or anorexia nervosa ...There is a danger of slipping into depression.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Most of the time, yes, they are oppressive. There is relentless perusal of bombastic standards of beauty and we wish to be like someone else. The individual becomes susceptible to identity crisis which takes a toll on his psychology and personality development.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats They feel isolated, worthless and excluded...all leading to low self esteem in them
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats  For persons with disabilities such ideas lead to distortion of concept of self. When persons feel bad about themselves there is self doubt and self devaluation
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats A curve in back is considered sexy and beautiful but if the angle of that same curve increases it gets a medical name and thus becomes repulsive and ugly...and the person is desexualised
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo Triggered by ableism the most desired thing remains is ‚Äòfixing‚Äô the outward appearance and that becomes a never ending challenge for persons with disabilities.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats The stigma attached to disabilities is profound in our society and persons with disabilities are seen as deformed, disfigured and many times even ugly.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats And for the same reason persons with disabilities often face barriers and challenges in the sexual expression as they are not considered beautiful according to oppressive standards set by the society and as a result they internalize this kind of oppression.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats It includes the expression of our sexual thoughts, feelings, desires, fears, hopes, and dreams. And as soon as we accept ourselves and our desires we would would feel beautiful and then can truly experience a mind-blowing sexual experience with another person..
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats Sexual Expression is form to express sexual instincts. It describes not only sexual activities we engage in but ways we communicate and present ourselves to the world as a sexual being. We all have unique ways of sexual expression.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo Sexuality itself is beautiful. Feeling sexual is feeling beautiful. And at the end of the day, feeling beautiful and sexy comes from our core. #TARSHIChat
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats As far as sexuality is concerned, Sexuality for me is a language by which I am able to express myself as a sexual being. It is a language of body which not only includes physical side but also our spiritual side.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo #TARSHIChats No one really feels sexy unless he/she is fully in touch with the sexual self! Self beauty is our thoughts, the way we love and who we are as human beings.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo Beauty is far beyond the clothing we may or may not fit in, how perfect our body is or isn‚Äôt and the comparisons we make to others. When we turn our insecurities into self-acceptance is what being truly beautiful is. #TARSHIChats
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @tarshingo To me actual beauty is feeling comfortable in your own skin..Feeling beautiful is a matter of self-acceptance. Beauty is something that is neutral and flexible. It can be molded into a pattern that we as individuals choose. #TARSHIChats
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai My pleasure to be here today
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Yes it is very unfortunate.. polio has been eradicated but polio survivors are still there...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai With all due respect to doctors, I would say they could have educated my parents and me about Post Polio Syndrome. But I think they themselves were not well educated in this area. Now if I have to survive I have to ask for support and help..No other way out!
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai I agree that my parents put me to rigorous exercises and were tough when I used to refuse wearing my leg braces but I cannot and will not blame them because they wanted to see physical improvement in me...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai The support from my family proved to be my savior. In the absence of that I would not have been able to achieve what all I have accomplished...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai @FeminismInIndia Thank you so much!
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai I always try to speak about it in my writings and in my activism. I want to empower and enable other women like me so that they may try to learn from my experiences. I try to bring out all those issues to the surface level which have never been spoken of..
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai My recent article is based on this very idea. Trying to overcompensate is very exhausting and drains a whole lot of not only physical but also emotional energy....
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai I have been supporting my old parents for many years. Doing household hold work is expected of from Indian women. I know I am unable to do that so I make sure that I can buy such services.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Women in our society are seen as caregivers. They have stereotype gender roles to perform which I was unable to do. There was again that desire to compensate why I as a woman could not do. I took the role of bread winner of my family
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai In psychology this is called Sublimation.When we're faced with the dissonance of uncomfortable thoughts, we create psychic energy. This has to go somewhere. Sublimation channels this energy away from destructive acts and into something that is socially acceptable or creative
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Yes it has impacted every bit of my existence. I have tried to take care of my old parents more than anybody in our near ones could do. Same is true in area of romance and my married life. I try to make sure that my husband has no chance to complain for anything...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai My work, my writings and accolades in a way served as a bandage to the emotional pain that had many times bruised my heart and my soul for not being able to perform my womb based role as a women..
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai I did not have boy friends and men did not find me a dating and marriage material, so I tried develop my intellectual faculties and so on‚Ä¶.When my age mates were getting married, I was continuing my higher education‚Ä¶
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Women with disabilities are doubly jeopardized; there is no doubt in this. I could not wear sexy dresses like my age mate and go to parties, so I tried to get more academic degrees!
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Yes poetry did not clip my wings in any way...I have always believed in power of words..It helped me express my inner most feelings, fears, apprehensions and even my dreams
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai But yes sometimes it was very lonely when all the students used to go play ground during the games period. But for that even I found a way out to prove myself better. I started writing poetry when no one in my class could even think of doing.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Fortunately my school and my classmates were very supportive. When they found me getting better scores then them, they used to take help in studies from me and was it a gratifying experience. I found myself better than them even in the presence of my so called physical deficits.
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai I went to regular school on for 4 years and it was again a challenge. One school agreed to give me classes on ground floor. I was conditioned since my childhood that it is the education which can compensate my physical deficits and education alone could give me independence...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai It brought me awareness of my condition..Unless we are aware of the presence of a problem we can't strategize to find solutions...Awareness is the first step in solution finding..I did'nt get depressed rather I started working the direction of finding means to cope up
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai This realization came a bit late. When I was doing my masters in psychotherapy I deeply studied about personalities. And I could easily relate myself with Type A one. And moreover it was around the same time that my PPS symptoms had started appearing...
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai I am a person who has accepted, acknowledged and adapted well in the changing conditions...my life has been full of adjustments and readjustments...And according to Darwin I find myself to be the fittest in that respect
Name: Abha Khetarpal

Text: @povmumbai Hi...its my pleasure to be here today
Name: Abha Khetarpal
